the osmotic pressure of the polymer. This pressure is the major driving force for gel swelling.56‚Äì59 In this context, by ‚Äúosmotic pressure of the polymer,‚Äù we refer to the equilibrium pressure difference between a ternary (water-polymer-salt) solution and a respective binary (water-salt) solution across a membrane impermeable to the polymer only. Figure 3 depicts the osmotic pressure of PAAm in solutions containing the sodium salts at 0.75 molal concentration. Similar experiments were
